      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification performed using the method of manufactured solutions for the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations and the power-law hemolysis transport equation. Observed order of accuracy consistent with theoretical second-order convergence rate. Verification report archived in project repository with traceability to solver version."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Three-level systematic mesh refinement study conducted per ASME V&V 20 GCI methodology. Refinement ratio r = 1.5 applied uniformly. GCI on peak volume-averaged shear stress: 1.4%; GCI on NIH: 1.8%. Both below the 5% threshold specified for MRL 2. Temporal discretization assessed separately with time-step halving; pressure and velocity fields converged within 0.3% change. Achieved level exceeds requirement due to rigorous three-level study."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions documented in FDA benchmark protocol. Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water mixture, 36% v/v) properties measured at 37°C and matched to simulation inputs within 2%. Flow rates and rotational speeds set to match five COU operating points. Test temperature controlled to ±0.5°C. Inlet turbulence intensity measured with LDV and applied as boundary condition."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed for NIH and pump head across all five operating points. Experimental uncertainty quantified using ASME V&V 20 procedures (Type A and B uncertainties combined). Simulation predictions fall within experimental uncertainty bands at four of five points; at the fifth point the relative error is 6.2%, within the 10% acceptance threshold for MRL 2. Comparison metrics tabulated in validation report VR-HEMOLYSIS-BENCH-COMPARISON."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), which is the regulatory-accepted metric for pump-induced blood damage per ASTM F1841. Secondary QoI is pump head (pressure rise), which governs hydraulic loading. Both QoIs are directly relevant to the COU decision criterion (RH < 1). The hemolysis power-law model parameters are calibrated against the same blood analog used in bench testing, ensuring relevance of the computational QoI to the physical phenomenon."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Validation activities conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry, which is the same device class and flow regime as the COU device. Operating conditions in validation experiments span the COU envelope (2–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Geometric fidelity between validation model and COU model confirmed by dimensional inspection report. Validation scenario rated high relevance to COU per ASME V&V 40 relevance rubric."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-mrl2-scoped",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is addressed within the discretization error and code verification factors for MRL 2. Separate assessment of iterative convergence errors is scoped out because residuals are monitored to machine-precision levels (RMS residuals < 1e-6 for all equations) and the solver vendor provides documented iterative error bounds for the turbulence model employed (SST k-omega). No additional standalone assessment is required at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-mrl2-scoped",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is scoped out at MRL 2 for this COU. The simulation workflow is executed by credentialed CFD analysts with documented training records. A peer-review checklist covering boundary condition setup, material property assignment, and post-processing scripts was completed and archived. The checklist constitutes sufficient use-error mitigation at MRL 2 without requiring a separate formal human-factors study."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Model form assessment covers (1) turbulence model selection: SST k-omega chosen based on published benchmark comparisons for confined rotating flows with adverse pressure gradients; (2) hemolysis model: power-law Giersiepen-Wurzinger correlation with Heuser-Opitz exponents, validated against RBC lysis data in literature; (3) non-Newtonian blood rheology: Carreau-Yasuda model applied with parameters from viscometry of the test fluid. Model form uncertainty estimated at ±12% on NIH, within the MRL 2 acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-mrl2",
      "rationale": "All model inputs documented in the boundary condition dataset (bindsDataset entry 3). Fluid properties measured experimentally; geometric inputs derived from CMM inspection of physical hardware with dimensional tolerances ±0.05 mm. Inlet velocity profiles extracted from LDV measurements. Sensitivity analysis performed on the three highest-uncertainty inputs (viscosity, inlet turbulence intensity, rotational speed); combined effect on NIH is 8.3%, within MRL 2 acceptance threshold of 15%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-mrl2-scoped",
      "rationale": "Test samples factor is scoped out at MRL 2 because the validation experiments use a blood analog fluid (glycerol-water) rather than human blood, consistent with ASTM F1841 and FDA guidance for pump hemolysis bench testing. Sample-to-sample biological variability is therefore not applicable. Fluid batch consistency confirmed by viscometry measurements before and after each test series; variation less than 1.5%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/equivalency-mrl2-scoped",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters between simulation and physical test is addressed within the model inputs and test conditions factors at MRL 2. A separate equivalency assessment is scoped out because the simulation boundary conditions are derived directly from the same experimental measurements used in the validation comparison, ensuring input equivalency by construction. Dimensional analysis confirms dynamic similarity (Reynolds number match within 0.8%) across all five operating points."
